06/04/2006
BRUSSELS, Belgium -- The European Commission on Wednesday (5 April) voiced strong support for plans to establish a free trade zone in southeast Europe. 
Leaders from the area are expected to launch the initiative at a meeting Thursday in Bucharest. 
The plan is to expand the existing Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA). 
to include Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Macedonia, Moldova, Serbia-Montenegro and Kosovo. 
CEFTA currently includes Bulgaria, Croatia and Romania. 
(AP - 05/04/06)
